%S A396355 1,1,1,4,1,1,1,0,1,1,10,1,10,1,1,1,1,1,0,5,1,10,1,0,1,4,1,1,10,1,1,10,
%T A396355 10,0,1,1,1,0,1,0,10,1,1,1,4,1,10,1,1,22,0,1,1,1,10,0,1,10,1,1,1,0,1,
%U A396355 1,22,1,10,1,1,1,0,10,10,10,10,1,1,10,1,10,0
%N A396355 a(n) is the number of integer-sided triangles (x <= y <= z) with circumradius R = A339952(n) such that gcd(x, y, z, R) = 1.
%C A396355 For any integer-sided triangle (x, y, z) with integer circumradius R and gcd(x, y, z, R) = 1, one has R in A339952. Proof: Let x <= y <= z be integers and R an integer circumradius. Then x = 2*R*sin X, y = 2*R*sin Y, z = 2*R*sin Z, so sin X, sin Y, sin Z are rational, and R = x*y*z/(4*A). Any rational sine has the form sin T = 2*a*b/(a^2 + b^2) with gcd(a,b) = 1 and a + b odd. From x = 2*R*sin X we get (a^2 + b^2)*x = 4*R*a*b, hence (a^2 + b^2) | 4*R. Doing the same for a second angle gives (c^2 + d^2) | 4*R. A prime p == 3 (mod 4) cannot divide a^2 + b^2 (else p | a and p | b, contradicting gcd(a,b) = 1), and similarly for c^2 + d^2; thus these numbers have only factors 2 or p == 1 (mod 4). Choose two angles with gcd(a^2 + b^2, c^2 + d^2) = 1. Then (a^2 + b^2)*(c^2 + d^2) | 4*R and is a sum of two squares, hence 4*R is a sum of two squares. Therefore every prime p == 3 (mod 4) divides R to an even exponent; write R = e^2 + o^2 with e > 0 even and o odd. Thus R is in A339952.
%C A396355 Conversely, for any R = e^2 + o^2 with e even > 0 and o odd, the right triangle [2*(e^2 - o^2), 4*e*o, 2*(e^2 + o^2)] has integer sides and circumradius R; hence 4*R | x*y*z and A = x*y*z/(4*R) is an integer.
%C A396355 Although every R in A339952 is the circumradius of some integer-sided triangle, such a triangle need not be primitive in the strong sense gcd(x, y, z, R) = 1; hence a(n) can be 0 for some n (e.g., R = 45).
%C A396355 a(n) = 2*k - (k mod 2) for R = A339952(n) = p^k. Proof: By the sum‑of‑two‑squares theorem, a prime power p^k appears as X^2 + Y^2 with p==1 (mod 4) only. For such p, there are k + 1 primitive “directions” of representation; exactly k of them have parity X even, Y odd with X>0 (if k is odd there is one extra odd + odd direction, not counted here). Strong‑primitive triangles arise by pairing these directions; this doubles the count, except that for odd k one symmetry class does not contribute. Hence a(n) = 2k - (k mod 2).
%H A396355 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_theorem_on_sums_of_two_squares">Fermat's theorem on sums of two squares</a>
%F A396355 a(n) = 2*e - (e mod 2) for A339952(n) = p^e.
%e A396355 For R = A339952(4) = 25 = 5^2 one has the a(4) = 2*2 - (2 mod 2) = 4 triangles [14, 30, 40], [14, 48, 50], [30, 30, 48], [40, 40, 48].
%p A396355 A396355List := proc(N)
%p A396355     local a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h, i, j, k, l, m, n, o, p, q, r, s, t, u, v, w, x, y, z;
%p A396355     b := ceil((N / 0.38) * (1 + sqrt(ln(max(16, N))))); e := table();
%p A396355     do
%p A396355         for c from 2 by 2 to isqrt(b) do
%p A396355             for d from 1 by 2 to isqrt(b - c^2) do
%p A396355                 g := c^2 + d^2; if type(g, odd) then e[g] := true end if
%p A396355             end do
%p A396355         end do;
%p A396355         if numelems(e) < N then b := ceil(3*b/2) else break end if
%p A396355     end do;
%p A396355     f := [op(1 .. N, sort([indices(e, 'nolist')]))];
%p A396355     a := table();
%p A396355     for n to N do
%p A396355         g := f[n]; h := g^2; i := 2*g; a[g] := 0; e := table();
%p A396355         for x from 1 while x^2 <= 3*h do
%p A396355             v := igcd(x, g); w := iquo(g, v);
%p A396355             for y from x to i do
%p A396355                 j := min(x + y - 1, i);
%p A396355                 if irem(x, 4) = 0 or irem(y, 4) = 0 then m := 1
%p A396355                 elif irem(x, 2) = 0 or irem(y, 2) = 0 then m := 2
%p A396355                 else m := 4
%p A396355                 end if;
%p A396355                 p := ilcm(iquo(w, igcd(y, w)), m);
%p A396355                 q := y + irem(p - irem(y, p), p); if q > j then next end if;
%p A396355                 s := x*y; t := y - x; u := x + y;
%p A396355                 for z from q to j by p do
%p A396355                     if h*(u + z)*(t + z)*(z - t)*(u - z) = (s*z)^2 then
%p A396355                         k := igcd(x, y, z); l := iquo(x, k); o := iquo(y, k); r := iquo(z, k);
%p A396355                         if igcd(k, g) = 1 then
%p A396355                             if not assigned(e[[l, o, r]]) then e[[l, o, r]] := true; a[g] := a[g] + 1 end if
%p A396355                         end if
%p A396355                     end if
%p A396355                 end do
%p A396355             end do
%p A396355         end do
%p A396355     end do;
%p A396355     [seq(a[f[n]], n = 1 .. N)]
%p A396355 end proc:
%p A396355 A396355List(81);
